The triskelion (triskele) symbol appears in many early cultures, the first in Malta (4400–3600 BC) and in the astronomical calendar at the megalithic tomb of Newgrange in Ireland.

Meaning of the Triskele

The meaning depends on the time and culture. Some of these meanings include: life-death-rebirth, spirit-mind-body, mother-father-child, past-present-future, power-intellect-love, and creation-preservation-destruction.

It is also believed to represent the three Celtic worlds; the spiritual world, the present world and the celestial world.​

description.text:
This is case for a raspberry pi Zero made to fit a SPAM can, 200g size, the small one.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=anwy2MPT5RE

I'm using it to run Pi Hole an adblocker that sits on your network and acts as the DNS server and refuses to serve you adverts.
The display shows how well its doing and is an OLED 128x32 . There is also a push button between the GPIO pins so that it can do a remote shutdown and a recovery if needed. Spam Key also added on the top for detail.
I printed this (luckily) without support, but depending on your printer you might want to add supports to baseplate.

Once you have your SPAM i suggest making a Reuben Spam sandwich. Fry the SPAM, add some Gruyere cheese, Sauerkraut, Dijon mustard and thousand island dressing. Pop it all under the grille and you have both a delicious snack and a Pi case.

description.text:
Generally speaking, I print the aircraft first, then check the tolerances on the stand by printing just the peg. I then putt a caliper to the joining cube slots and scal the cube/stand appropriately. I have done some minor scaling of the stand, so it might fit as is, but check the comments to check other people's success scaling.

"The original program cost estimate of £70 million met huge overruns and delays, with the program eventually costing £1.3 billion. It was this extreme cost that became the primary factor in the production run being much smaller than anticipated. Another major factor impacting the viability of all SST programs was in how supersonic route options were eventually limited to ocean-crossing only to prevent sonic boom disturbance on populated areas. With only 7 airframes each being operated by the English and French, the per-unit cost were impossible to recoup, so the French and British governments absorbed the airframe and development costs. British Airways and Air France were able to operate Concorde at a profit, in spite of very high maintenance costs, because of this steep government subsidy. British Airways paid £1 per aircraft, so its entire Concorde fleet cost the airline £7."

I thought I'd include that little tidbit from the wikipedia page. It's incredible to think that even charging $7995 a seat, they still couldn't keep that jet profitable after all of the maintenance costs.

I learned a lot about this aircraft while modeling it! I tried to go a little bit retro with the stand. Their logo just screamed '70s' to me. I gave BAC all the credit, even though this was a joint effort with Sud Aviation. Sud later became Aerospatiale and BAC later became BAE systems.

Just another incredible aircraft. I'm pretty impressed with the engineering that went into these planes, even 50 years ago.

description.text:
Millennium blades vanilla inserts are pretty bad. My organizers are somewhat space efficient and provide a bit of in-game utility. I particularly like the side-loading money organizers since you can easily count and pull bills from the center taped area.

The first version of the card holders has tall walls (orange in the pictures), but pulling out individual sets is challenging and wastes filament. The shorter walls allow you to pull sets from the sides without having to take out the whole section. I included a support piece that helps prevent the game mats and rule book from possibly pressing down on the cards. I do not recommend using the tall walls.

The organizers are no taller than 60 mm so the game mats and rule book can sit on top.

My penny sleeves are 95 mm x 68 mm while a card is 89 mm x 64 mm.

The token lid isn't quite as snug as I wanted it to be at 200 microns. I recommend saving filament and printing the lidless version.

One of the pictures shows an example fit of set divider labels with about 1 cm headway found here: https://boardgamegeek.com/filepage/132430/millennium-blades-card-dividers

I do not plan on owning the MB set rotation or any expansions in the near future (the vanilla game has plenty of replay-ability), so I can't comment on how well this design accommodates them. I may re-design the organizers should I obtain any expansions.

Everything fits relatively snug with no bowing of the box walls.

I hide a pen behind one of the money holders :)

title: Spirit Halloween Proton Pack Mod Parts

description.text:
Modification parts for the Spirit Halloween Proton Pack.

Filler plates are designed to be glued in behind the area in question (speaker grille, molded-in Clippard after it's cut off) and then the area should be filled with epoxy or spot putty and sanded/blended smooth.

The Powercell Lens prints great in translucent blue PLA. You must print it solid, with supports, and the small side against the build surface. The supports should easily pick off, and the lens should pop right into place from behind. Flame polish the surface if you want, just be careful doing it.

The V-Hook outer filler plate is actually asymmetrical. If it doesn't fit one way, rotate it 180* and try again. The inner plate however should just drop into place and index with the center pin. Remove the old center piece first (4 screws). These parts are designed to beef up the area when installing a regular V-Hook.

The loom clamps engage the 1/2 Polypropylene loom via the small teeth each one has. Note which is inserted from the rear (looking at the inside of the pack) and which is from the top (looking at the outside of the pack). Each will need to be curved slightly to lay into the pack body - do this by gently heating, then pressing against the cyclotron body so that they take up the proper curve.

Update - 10/2/2017:
Added the small and large long Dale resistors that go on the Ion Arm. These now have 1/8 holes in the middle to fit the 1/8 tubing used on the Spirit packs. Had to do a ton of remodeling to fix the original files, which had huge mesh issues.

Update - 10/3/2017:
Added a remodeled Brass Elbow, which mounts on an easier-to-redrill 1/4" hole, and accepts 1/8 tubing.

Update - 10/4/2017:
Added nut-capturing mount for mounting the pack shell to the motherboard. These use 5mm nuts. I recommend using nylocks and lightly gluing them in.

Update 10/6/2017:
Added the missing second booster tube connection. Make the actual booster-tube side out of a small chunk of 1/4" corrugated loom, connect with blue 1/8" tubing.

Update 10/18/2017:
Added a Spirit Wand to 1/2" (Stock) Loom Coupler

Update 10/25/2017:
Added a much-asked-for full Guntrack, V-Hook (Male and Female) and fully integrated V-Hook mount on the pack. The peg on the wand sticks through part of the guntrack, so be sure to use the WAND POST CUTTING JIG to trim it to length. Install on the peg and cut off anything that sticks out, then remove and install the guntrack. M3x8mm screws used in all places, must be flat head to clearance.

Second Update 10/25/2017:
Updated the Booster Tube Connection model to R2, made slightly larger and better matched the ribbing on the pack.

Update 10/31/2017:
Happy Halloween! Removed Clippard Insert files, as I designed a new one for my replacement full-size Clippard model. See my Things and check it out!

Update 11/11/2017:
Added totally remodeled Booster Tube. Simply print and glue in place - don't bother with the stock screws. Also added an HGA Replacement Cap. Glue into place and clear the screw hole paths with a 5mm drill bit, then install 4 M5 socket head cap screws.

Update 11/12/2017:
Added a Dale PH25 Resistor model. Remixed from MileyORiley's Proton Pack files, no .skp for this because it's a direct mesh manipulation done in Meshmixer. I resized the model to correctly size up against the real Dale PH25 on my full size proton pack.

title: Tevo Tarantula Narrow Modular X Carriage

description.text:
If you use this, please tell me if you run into any clearance issues! I will be happy to help fix them for you. I designed this around my upgrades, so it should work in most cases.

Please give suggestions for improvements, or for something else I should model!

This is a redesign of _MSA_'s modular X carriage for the Tevo Tarantula. I also used the belt holder design from Elzariant's X carriage. It addresses some of the problems raised by _MSA_'s design, namely that it's narrower, and has two wheels at the top rather than at the bottom. It also lacks a rear wall, so it should allow for things to be mounted on the back of the X axis rail.

  • Should print in orientation as shown in the blue Thingiverse model pictures, aside from belt.stl made by Elzariant.
  • The top inside M5 bolts on the stock Z carriages are too long, and will likely extend too far in and collide with the belt holders. To remedy this, thread some of the extra M5 nuts that came with the printer all the way onto the M5 bolts. This should shorten the amount that it sticks out the back enough to prevent the collision. If not, add another washer or two. Or just remove the wheel entirely, it's probably not that crucial to keep it.
  • I recommend printing with at least 4 perimeter walls, for strength.
  • P1 is the only piece that needs support, for the tower part that has the overhang. I would like to eliminate the need for supports here, if you have any suggestions, let me know.
  • Note the length of the M4 bolts being used in the 6 mounting holes on the front/back, as they may scratch your rail if they are too long. I tried to increase the distance slightly, but anything longer than 14mm is likely too long.
  • Should only require parts that came with your printer, as well as some additional M4 nuts and bolts.
  • Back plate is not required, but recommended if you do not need to attach anything directly to the back of the rail (such as a single Z in the center of the X rail rather than the side).

title: Owen's Bowden clamp: tightening cone improvement (parametric + inner rings)

description.text:
Update: tweak your own according to your printer and setup: http://www.thingiverse.com/apps/customizer/run?thing_id=25636 ! I had some trouble printing an acceptable cone for the two bowden clamp things: they were a bit slippy on the inside unless I destroyed them in the riser by screwing them too much... This one:
  • features inner rings to add radial but non-uniform clamp force on the tube, which works really nicely
  • is (still) fully parametric so you can tune it to your tube diameter, riser internal diameter and printer fuzziness...
    • Thanks to owen of course for this very nice thing :)

By default, the provided STL was for the feeder end bowden clamp thing by pit3k but I guess it would work just alike for the original hot end clamp by owen (it is not based on the original openscad files though, I was too lazy to dig into them) Else, just download the free openscad, load the scad source file, fine-tune the constants as needed, press F6, export it as STL and you're done. It has the following values: // Internal ripples
rippler=0.3; // internal ripple width (at base of cone, will be zero on top)
rippleh=1; // internal ripple height
ripples=2; // internal ripple spacing (will be added to rippleh, ie one 1-mm shoulder with 2mm in between) // Cone body
ir=6; // internal radius (bowden tube diameter)
ch=16; // cone height
or1=9.2; // outside radius (big one)
or2=7.8; // outside radius (small one)
gap=2; // width of the vertical opening Note that I first drilled (very slightly) the riser on my side to make it perfectly smooth, though the cone here should adapt to a variety of diameters on its own. Let me know if you need/use other settings, so I could add STL variants to the thing. Printed with Cura RC4 (I upgraded from RC3 b/c it failed all the time for me: the head was moving way too fast?!), with:
  • raft
  • 0.1mm layer height
  • 0.8mm wall thickness
  • 60mm speed
  • 20% fill density (almost no relevant though)
  • "low" temperature + fan
    • Still room to improve my print (sorry InfiniTTTy: no way for a batsymbol here!)

title: Original Prusa i3 MK2 Z-Axis Clip on Fan Mount

description.text:
After doing my first 8+ hour print, I noticed how hot the stepper motors were. I found several great examples for mounting 40mm fans to the Nema 17 stepper motors. The Z-Axis motors still get plenty of workout and get plenty warm, especially on objects with lots of fine details and/or if you are printing at higher speeds.

However, I never found anything specific to the Z-Axis motors found on the original Prusa i3 MK2. I was inspired by other designs, mainly:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1409754
-and-
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:31405
...but neither of these would fit the Z-axis.

The Original Prusa i3 MK2 and MK2S both have unique brackets that hold the Z-Axis stepper motors, but at the same time these same brackets prevent the use of full wrap around designs.

My goals for the design were two fold:

  1. Design a bracket that would mount easily without having to disassemble ANY of the printer. Disassembly could result in re-calibration. No one has time for that.
  2. Design a bracket that would sufficiently cool the motor, but at the same time deflect air down and away from the heated print bed. If I had designed a simple open air bracket, the air would be blasted everywhere after bouncing off the front of the stepper motor.

To meet these goals, this fan mount is a clip on design that simply slides around and fits neatly resting it's weight on the Nema 17 motor's own grooves. The walls are thin (1mm) to allow the plastic to flex and fit around the motor and at the same time provide air channels that help cool the sides and deflect air downwards.

You must print two of these, one for each Z-Axis motor on the Original Prusa i3 MK2. The left and right side motor mounts are identical, so my design works on both.

The screw holes are sized to fit M3 screws and will self thread into the plastic. Purchase screws 5mm longer than the thickness of your fan. For example, to mount a 40mm x 20mm fan (like the one in my pictures), you will need M3 x 25mm screws. If your fan has countersunk holes, get 5mm shorter screws. You can always use a small washer to help. If your screws are too long, THEY WILL PREVENT THE MOUNT FROM FITTING ONTO THE MOTOR PROPERLY. Nuts and lock washers are NOT necessary to mount the fan. If you do use nuts, take care to use ones thinner than 5mm.

I used the recommended settings for the Prusa's version of Slic3r included with the printer. Specifically .15 resolution, 20% infill, and no supports or rafts. Mine are printed in PLA, but feel free to attempt to print them using other materials.

This fan mount may work on other printers with Nema 17 stepper motors, but it was specifically designed for the Original Prusa i3 MK2 and MK2S and I do not guarantee compatibility with others. Prusa has recently announced the MK3 for release later this year. Based on the pictures, the Z-axis motor mounts appear unchanged from the MK2 series, so I strongly suspect these might fit the MK3 when it comes out. If it doesn't fit the MK3, feel free to remix it.

description.text:
This thing is an original car phone holder specifically designed for the Nissan Leaf (up to 2017 model, I believe - although mine is 2014). It is a branch of a previous project from about 2 years ago that would fit my Nexus 6 only and was never published but, despite being printed with PLA and having to stand 40+ degrees Celsius during the summer, worked perfectly since then. Since I recently bought a new phone it wasn't good anymore for me, so I decided to go for a more adjustable design.

It is a modular concept made of 4 parts, so that it can easily be adapted to different phone models (either by just sliding the arms or by modifiyng their design) or even cars (although you will have to design your own car clip part for that). The source project is at https://cad.onshape.com/documents/9f5c360d6f7f580f74eaf987/w/0a8f2910bb7e10f9499f8ac0/e/9a6be3419e4396ef08d18ec3 so please feel free to improve it as much as you like.

How I print this:

  • Material: PLA. Haven't tried ABS or PETG yet but I suppose it would make for a much better finish, especially if you smooth ABS with acetone.
  • No need for support when printing, but I suggest to use some skirt, specially for the body part.
  • Any layer height should do, as the tolerances are not excessively tight.
  • Print the arm STL twice. As they are simmetrical, you only need to turn one of them upside down as shown in pics.
  • Use duct tape on the clip inside part to avoid scratches to the car (as show in pics).
  • Use layers of duct tape on arms as shown in pics untill you find the optimal grip (arms should slide with some force but not be stuck).

After printing, test the arms having them slide into the main body slits, and apply layers of duct tape (or glue if your'e bold and don't plan to use more than one phone) to find the right amount of resistance that will keep your phone firm enough while allowing adjustments to accomodate other mobiles. Once you've done that, snap the clip part onto the Leaf's left air vent above the screen, possibly applying some duct tape in order to avoid scratches to the car's plastic, and slide the main body vertically in it's hole. It should fit nicely without further adjustments.

A word of caution (or two):

  • I never re-print the car clip part after re-designing it with OnShape. Although I believe it's identical to the original, I never actually tried.
  • Please verify that YOUR phone sits steadily in the support before accelerating the car, or it may fall (happened to me on a previous version) and eventually break. YOU HAVE BEEN WARNED.

title: skimmer/vacuum cleaner hose adapter for swimming pools

description.text:
I had a very large adapter to plug my vacuum cleaner hose into the skimmer of my swimming pool. And it finnaly broke (UV?). So I designed this smaller one.
It consists of two opposed cones, so they just plug in a standard 40mm pool hose (well, that's a standard here) and on the other side to the bottom of the skimmer (which is probably not standard!)

Update: you may prefer to use the service described at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:26096 to generate STL files for your own diameters By the way, it proved easier to handle than the stock one b/c the whole tube end is below the water surface in the skimmer. First of all, check the flexible tube and skimmer bottom diameter. The openscad file here is set up with:
  • flexible tube diameter is 40mm and the plug height is 30mm
  • skimmer bottom evacuation hole is 45mm, with 22mm depth (no need for a tight coupling there, b/c of the depressurized flow!)
    The cones diameters are the same diameters with 1mm more on the big side and 1mm less on the finer side.
    • There are (probably useless) internal structures for added rigidity. Well, they also make the thing more interesting to print! ;-) By the way, make sure there is a filter before your pump for large objects ;)

description.text:
Not sure what to bring to a birthday party? Print one of those sweet vouchers and surprise your friends with an extraordinary idea.
Tell them that you can print whatever they want on your 3D printer for the amount specified on the label.

You can print these vouches with multiple colors, even with just a singe nozzle! Have a look at the instructions below.

The following vouchers exist:

  • German: 10, 15, 20 and 50 Euro
  • English Euro: 10, 15, 20 and 50 Euro
  • English Dollar 10, 15, 20 and 50 Dollar

Happy gift giving!

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

15 %

Notes:

To print the vouchers with different colors, follow these steps:

  • After slicing your gcode file, use your prefeered gcode viewer or slicer to identify the first layer were the text printing starts. (with 0.2 mm layer height and Simplify3D, its layer 10 and 18)
  • Open your gcode file with any text editor you like and find the two layers, described above
  • Insert a new small gcode snipped (see below) before the layer start.
  • Now, print the model and swap the color when the printer pauses.

Code snippets

Here are two simple code snippets for pausing your printer. If you are using octoprint, you can add the advanced code snippet in the octoprint settings for all your prints.
No garantee that it works with your printer, just take it as an inspiration :) !

Simple (for Marlin printer firmware)

M0 ;pause printer

Advanced (for Marlin printer firmware)

G91 ; relative positioning
G0 Z5 ;raise z axis
G90 ;absolute positioning
G0 X0 Y0 F3000 ;move to park position
M0 ;pause printer
G0 X(PREV_X) Y(PREV_Y) F3000 ; move back to last position, replace (PREV_X) and (PREV_Y) !!
G91 ; relative positioning
G0 Z-5 ; lower z axis
G90 ; absolute positioning

author: jasonmrc

title: Creality CR-10 X axis horizontal leveling rulers system

description.text:
Eases to keep the leveling of the CR-10 X axis against the frame reference. Provides a visual clue for the leveling set up, and to check whether it become misaligned over time.

This is critical since the bed leveling relies on this and a tilted X axis and bed would produce skewed prints.

Printer:

Creality CR-10 S3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

10%

• The Creality CR-10 S models comes with the second Z threaded shaft loosened from its coupler to relieve the potential strains during transport, and the user must level the X axis' beam manually by means of rotating the shaft and tighten the coupler.

  • The Creality CR-10 upgrade kit to add a second motor also requires the user to level the Z axis manually during installation.

  • Even the base Creality CR-10 with a single Z axis motor may have the axe tilted because the carriage wheels gets loosened or misaligned.

In any case, the printer doesn't have any shared point of reference in both sides to properly measure them and figure out whether the X axis beam is leveled in reference with the frame (notice that later on, the axe will be the reference to level the bed, so a tilted axes means an equally tilted bed leading to skewed printings). Certainly you can place a ruler or a caliper next to the beam to measure its height at each side, but you cannot press it against any surface to ensure a perpendicular measure, and the error margin could be of a couple of millimeters. Besides, there's no simple way than to repeat the measuring to tell whether the axe misaligned and tilted over time.

This kit has four pieces:

Two rulers to glue against each pillar, between the rubbers and pressed all the way downwards against the bottom frame to ensure both will read the same, and two nails that hang from the carriages at each side, to be glued over the surface and pressed all the way upwards against the bottom of the X horizontal beam, such that both rulers and both nails are placed against the same reference points at both sides.

In my case, I used a black permanent marker to paint the ruler's face to make the measuring marks visually stand up by contrast.

Note: There are IMPORTANT notes at the bottom to read. Please READ THEM.

Left ruler placement. Right ruler placement. Left nail placement. Right nail placement Files

There are six STL files, four with each piece isolated, and two with pairs of pieces facing each other. I recommend printing them in pairs at once to ensure the same printing conditions and the same outcome. Even when the rulers intends to measure millimeters and centimeters, it's not really relevant whether the measures are correct, but that both rulers marks are at the same height and both nails have the same height, and by printing them separately you improve the chance of having unwanted differences.

CR-10S and upgraded CR-10
  1. Turn on the printer.
  2. Select Prepare->Auto Home at the menu.
  3. Select Prepate->Move Axis-Move 1 mm or Move 0.1 mm->Z Axis, and turn the dial to lift the X beam looking at the left ruler to make the nail match a marking (even better, the nail has a flat surface. Press a blade flat over the surface until being able to dig it inside a marking, this is more precise than the mere visual clue).
  4. Select Prepare->Dissable steppers.
  5. Turn off the printer.
  6. Manually rotate the right Z axis shaft either way, to make the right nail match the same height from the left side (if using a blade, you do the same for a more accurate measure).

Notice: some people worries about both Z motors's coils not being properly aligned inside, thus even when synchronized while working, when turning the printer off one of them may be stopped at a half step and accommodating itself to rest at a whole step with an undesired turn that, over time, may lead to a misalignment. If so, instead of disabling the steppers and turning off the printer (4th and 5th steps), leave it turned on and engaged, losen the threaded shaft from the shaft coupler with the coupler's bolt and manually rotathe the shaft instead until reaching the desired height, and then disable the steppers (to let both motors at whole step rest), doble check the height, and tighten the shaft in the coupler.

Original, non upgraded CR-10

Losen the wheels from the carriages at each side and tighten them back once in the proper position. By screwing the wheels you'll notice they press against the rails.

Both the rulers and the nails must be carefully placed in tight places to prevent them from interfering with the mechanics.

  • Te rulers height matches the protuberance from the rubbers, they must be glued in between them ensuring they not protrude higher than the rubbers height, otherwise the carriage may bump or scratch against it when traveling on the Z plane. I recommend to present it sticking with tape first and slowly move the Z axis to ensure there's no contact before gluing it.

  • The nails must be glued aligned with the external side of the external rubber at each side, otherwise the headset carriage wheels will bump against it when travelling on the X plane. I recommend to present it sticking with tape and manually move the header carriage to ensure there's no contact before gluing it (see image 15).

  • The left nail must be more precisely aligned, since it may bump against the Z axis's end travel switch or its circuits when travelling down. When presenting it with tape, move the Z axis downwards to ensure there is no contact (see image 16).
Beware having enough clearance between the left nail and the switch as the nail travels downwards. Beware having enough clearance between the left nail and the headset carriage left wheel and the belt clip underneath, as the headset travels furthest to the left. DISCLAIMER

Do this mod at your own risk

Features:

  • The hotend can easily be swapped out. (for example, when I print in nylon I use 3mm while everything else is 1.75mm)

  • There is room under the carriage for many of the preexisting E3D fan ducts.

  • The spacers can be used to raise the carriage if needed. Otherwise make sure to use one of these to adjust the z-axis height: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:621440

  • The heater block is very exposed. Swapping out different sized nozzles is so easy!

  • I included a mounting point for future accessories.

  • The PCB can be installed on top of the carriage above the recessed screw hole.

  • The carriage movement is extremely smooth and quiet.

To connect the x-axis belt to the carriage: Drill and tap two small holes in the aluminum bearing housing. Secure belt with screws and large washers.

After the installation of my new GT2560+ and the 3DTouch I’ve restart use the original GEEETech firmware for mi Pro i3B…
…it work fine but I’ve integrate in this firmware some enhancement that I’d like:

  • A dedicated pin for the 3Touch, in order to leave original endstop on Z Min as emergency stop in case of error with 3DTouch (now the firmware look in same time Z Min and Z Probe pin during Z Home)
  • A define to manage the offset not only for Z_PROBE but also for Z_ENDSTOP, now if the input come from probe the firmware use the value present in Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER, but if the input come from endstop it use Z_ESTOP_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER.
  • Printing of Estimated Time to End just below of printing time, I’ve shorted 6 char the bar.
  • In the Prepare menu I’ve add the 4 3DTouch command (Reset/Autotest/Pin down/Pin Up).
  • In configuration.h I’ve put step_per_unit for T8, but you can found also the old line for M8.

title: Parallel solar charger
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The parallel solar charger is designed for conservation charging of standard lead batteries.
This device combines a solar charger, a distributor for up to three batteries in parallel and a convenient OEM connector for accessing the batteries. It is designed for a Phoenix Contact connector which is installed with the Cristec CPS3 OEM charger on bord of Bavaria Cruiser yachts. This connector is very conveniant as it allows to charge all batteries on bord via one plug. However it is very hard to find this connector. I tried with retailers (Conrad, Reichelt) as well as with the producer, but none would sell the connector individually. Minimum quantity was 50! So I had to come up with one for myself.

This charger includes a few electronic parts (Schottky diodes and fuses) to protect and balance the batteries. The diodes stop the most charged battery from cross charging the other ones and ensure that always the lowest battery is charged first. This allows to conservation charge all batteries with just one small solar panel (15 W will do).

The whole project is described in detail on my website: http://www.oe1cgs.at/ladeverteiler-fuer-solar-erhaltungsladung/
(Deutsch)

In addition to the printed parts and a simple PWM solar charger you will need the following items (bill of materials:

  • 4mm dia. brass rod, 140 mm Long
  • 4 nuts M4 to be glued into the connector
  • 2 nuts M3 to be glued into the connector
  • 4 screws M4*10 mm with flat hat
  • 4 self-tapping screws 3x12 mm
  • 4 self-tapping screws 3x6 mm

Printer:

BQ Hephestos i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

20%

The trickiest part is the connector, more specifically the contacts. The 4 mm brass rods have to be cut in 4 equal pieces each 35 to 40 mm in length. Then drill a hole with 2 or 2,5 mm in one end of each piece, about 6 mm deep. Later you will solder (60 W or more iron recommended) the wires in those holes. Now you have to bring 14 mm of the opposite side to the holes down to a diameter of 3,5 mm. This diameter is required by the matching part of the connector towards the batteries. If you have a lathe at hand this should'nt be any problem. I did'nt, so a I had to come up with another method: Mount the rods in a drill and first with a rasp and later with some sand paper bring the diameter down to 3,5 mm. Round the tops, solder the wires and glue the rods with some 2 component rasin into the connector. The 3,5 mm front ends should be even with the connecter.

The other part needing some special attention is the simple electronic circuit with the 3 fuses and diodes. There are several ways to do this. I used some prototype PCB board to solder the parts and molded the board into the respective 3D-printed part.

title: Manfrotto Modo 785B Tripod Cam Lock Lever
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I picked up a Manfrotto 785B tripod from a charity shop recently for $5 :)
Unfortunately, it had one broken cam lever :(

It appears from a little research that the cam locks are generally the part that fails, but I thought I'd share this anyway in case someone else could use it.

I modelled the replacement based on the 3rd lever from the bottom.

The lever may also work for the other sections of the tripod, as they just appear to lengthen as they go from bottom to top.
The business end is probably the same for all of them.

Remove the small pin that holds the lever in place (in the unlocked position).
While resting the cam lobe on a table, I used a small screwdriver and hammer to tap the pin out.
Replace the broken lever with the newly printed one and tap the pin back into place.

description.text:
So, I'm browsing All3DP when I see this Pi-Powered mini Gamecube from @sparrows89

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2539417

And I think, "Yeah, that's pretty coo--!" and I see that Zelda disc just sitting there on the table, and now I'm mad. Granted, we're talking first-world problems levels of mad, but mad nonetheless. I hate it, hate it, hate it, hate it when people put their discs on tables. I don't care how careful you think you are or how indestructible you think your discs are or how little you think minor scratches affect your discs. STOP IT!

The Goddesses gave you a case for a reason.

Naked discs make Din, Farore, and Nayru cry. Why you gotta be all Ganon-like on them?

Anyway, I know this is one of those problems where the people who need this aren't the type to go printing workarounds for, y'know, putting their damn discs in their cases, but I also get that you've got these marathon sessions where you're chilling with your friends and you decide to change gears from Mario Kart to Smash Bros. and dealing with those snaps in the cases over and over again gets to be tedious. Seriously, I get it. Hey, remember playing Riven back in the CD-ROM days and you had to change discs every time you went to a different island? Remember how much that bloody sucked!?

It's for these purposes that I present to you, my fellow gamers, the disc nips (come on, you were all thinking it). the smallest ones can be used with GCN discs or full CD, DVD, BD... etc., while the two models with arms are specifically for Gamecube games. Don't worry, there's the tiniest bit of clearance between the upper surface of the arms and where the data part of the disc is, so you're not trading one bad surface for another.

Yeah, physical media is dying, but you can still give it a good life.

title: Garmin VIRB Elite Magnetic Vehicle Mount

description.text: This mount will allow you to stick your Garmin VIRB Elite to any ferrous surface with great strength using magnets out of a 3.5" hard drive.

Printing

Print top and bottom half of mount. ABS or PLA work just fine. Print at around 0.25mm layer thickness.

Assembly

  1. Take the two hard drive magnets and run the #6 screws through them so that the threads stick out the opposite side of the magnets. Stack the bottom half on top.

  2. Stick the Garmin mount base inside of the top half with the screw side sticking out. Slide this onto the bottom half. The hallowed out part of the top mount will be on the inside. The Garmin base will be sandwiched between the two halves.

  3. Tighten down a nut on the other side and screw down the Garmin arm and camera as normal.

So, after printing all my Trellis boxes, I realized I now had to actually solder the damn LEDs into the board. Some people are going to say, "Well, why don't you just bend the leads so they hook in place? Or, hey, how about that painter's tape stuff?"

Well, you lot can go straight to H E Double hockey sticks!

I'm sorry, that's not nice. I shall rephrase.

You lot can go straight to your respective ideology's place of eternal damnation and punishment, or, if your ideology lacks such a realm/state of mind, simply punch yourself in the stomach as hard as you possibly can. If you're not knocking the wind out of yourself, you're doing it wrong.

Yeah, dodged a bullet, right there, I did. (high-fives self)

In all seriousness, though, even with those workarounds (which I do use at times, I freely admit... believe me when I say I'm very winded right now as I write this), it's never easy to guarantee those LEDs will stay upright, and albeit you've got some wiggle room under those buttons, it's best they stay as upright as possible. The recesses in this aid should hold the LED at their base, that little lip where the anode and cathode come out of, so you'll see this little gap between your board and the aid. I tried accounting for the lip so the board would be flush with the aid, but this seemed to hold the LED straighter for some reason.

You can mix-match the parts some, use both the vertical and the horizontal mounts or two of one type depending on your setup or needs. Some modification might be needed. The side support-beams can be turned upside down to raise or lower the second row of blowers.
